prop-abstract-1612698044: Carse summarizes his argument, "There are at least two kinds of games: finite and infinite. A finite game is played for the purpose of winning, an infinite game for the purpose of continuing the play. Finite games are those instrumental activities - from sports to politics to wars - in which the participants obey rules, recognize boundaries and announce winners and losers. The infinite game - there is only one - includes any authentic interaction, from touching to culture, that changes rules, plays with boundaries and exists solely for the purpose of continuing the game. A finite player seeks power; the infinite one displays self-sufficient strength. Finite games are theatrical, necessitating an audience; infinite ones are dramatic, involving participants..

prop-abstract-1612698044: The book summarizes research that [[daniel-kahneman-1620203355]] conducted over decades, often in collaboration with Amos Tversky. It covers all three phases of his career: his early work concerning cognitive biases, his work on prospect theory, and his later work on happiness. The integrity of many of the priming studies cited in the book have been called into question in the midst of the psychological replication crisis, although the results of Kahneman's own studies have replicated.The main thesis is that of a dichotomy between two modes of thought: [[ref-system-1-1620203198]] is fast, instinctive and emotional; [[ref-system-2-1620203553]] is slower, more deliberative, and more logical. The book delineates rational and non-rational motivations/triggers associated with each type of thinking process, and how they complement each other, starting with [[daniel-kahneman-1620203355]]'s own research on loss aversion. From framing choices to people's tendency to replace a difficult question with one which is easy to answer, the book summarizes several decades of research to suggest that people have too much confidence in human judgement.

prop-title-1612697362: Transclusion expression
prop-abstract-1612698044: [[transclusion-1625221775]]s in the context of [[ipfoam-1612121966]]. Is how [[content-1625149127]] of an [[abstraction-reference-1612699252]] is inserted into a [[interplanetary-text-1612698201]] through a [[transform-1613076164]] 
---


# Notation

## Function notation

Since a [[transclusion-expression-1613026811]] is the product of a [[transform-1613076164]] applied into an [[[interplanetary-text-1612698201]] it can be written as function call

The function itself is the [[transform-1613076164]] (t) and the arguments are [[abstraction-reference-1612699252]]

`t (x, y)`

or as a [[ref-polish-notation-1626245743]] / [[s-expr-1626248935]]

`t x y`

a nested one:

Q: An [[transclusion-expression-1613026811]] composed exlclusively of inmutable elements and written as an [[s-expr-1626248935]] can be reduced to a Merkle Proof. Can we derive anything interesting from it?
`t1 (t2 x) y

## Named parameters

It is tempting to make a notation system that allows for `named parameters` but the only advantage I see would be to make it human-readable-friendly.
Given that the [[abstraction-reference-1612699252]] are long alphanumeric numbers, being human-friendly is not something to optimize for, specially since it's assumed that the writting will be assisted by the [[ipfoam-runtime-1614833118]]
The [[s-expr-1626248935]] are a much more elgant structure.

# Formating

## Format

> Likely the current decision wont be the right one. It needs to bee just good enough for now

The format should be able to be expressed sandalone but also embeded in text.

A [[json-1626280231]] array structure seems a natural way to express a [[transclusion-expression-1613026811]].

Pros
- It is [[ipld-1612088855]] compatible
- No need for custom parsers
- It can be extended if I need to add some sort of data that I'm currently not conceving.
- Can use [[json-1626280231]] objects as arguments. I believe an [[s-expr-1626248935]] expression we will need additional assumptions in order to write key-value pairs.
- The `{`,`}`,`[`,`]` characters used to tokenize [[json-1626280231]] are uncommon in [[natural-language-1613596219]] which is where they could be conflicting if we need to embed them in a text.
Cons
- There will be "unnecessary" `"` characters sorounding the  [[abstraction-reference-1612699252]]
- There will be "unnecessary" `,` to separate the array elements
  
In a simple [[transclusion-1625221775]] (no [[transform-1613076164]]s), compared to an [[s-expr-1626248935]], a [[json-1626280231]] array will have only the commas as and square brackets as extra, and the square brackets will be needed anyway as tokens to tokenize the [[interplanetary-text-1612698201]]

Q: Are thre any alternatives to [[json-1626280231]]? Would a new format make sense?
A: Likley, no need to prematurely optimize it now
  
## Composition

Assuming we use [[json-1626280231]] arrays to represent a [[transclusion-1625221775]] the following are possible compositions:
`a`: Argument: An [[abstraction-reference-1612699252]] or a valid [[json-1626280231]] value (string, number,object ,array, boolean, null)
`t`: Transform: An [[abstraction-reference-1612699252]]

### No [[transform-1613076164]]

No [[transform-1613076164]] is applied
Is the only occasion where the first argument doesn't make a reference to a [[transform-1613076164]]
E: `[a]`

### Simple

First element is a [[transform-1613076164]] the following are arguments
E: `[t,a,a]`

### Nested

E: `[t, a, [t,a]]`

### Multiple nesting

E: `[t, a,[t,[t,a,[t,a],[t,a]]]`

### With primitive types

E: `[t,1,4]` // `t` being a sum for exmple

### With objects

E: `[t,{"key1":value1,"key2":{"key21":true}}]`

### [[transform-1613076164]] is outcome of another [[transform-1613076164]]

- If the outcome of the inner [[transform-1613076164]] fits the requirements to be considered a [[transform-1613076164]] should be evaulated and executed as such.
  E: `[[t,a],a]`

## Runtime and evaluations

- Steps:The [[transclusion-1625221775]] will be evaluated from the leaves
- Single element is assumed to not have [[transform-1613076164]].
- A mal formatted [[json-1626280231]] [[transclusion-expression-1613026811]] inside [[interplanetary-text-1612698201]] will be ignored and presented as simple text. This also allows the use of the token characters to be used for [[natural-language-1613596219]] writting
- The [[transform-1613076164]] needs to define its arity. Could be infinite. But needs to be known.
- The [[transform-1613076164]] needs to express if a value is optional
- Empty values are represented by `null`, In case [[transclusion-1625221775]] alows optional arguments. See: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/21120999/representing-null-in-json/21122019

## Values

[[intent-identifier-1612383211]]
[[cid-1612383388]]

# Topology

## [[abstraction-reference-1612699252]]

Is the pointer that indicates what [[content-1625149127]] needs to be retrieved.

## [[content-1625149127]]

Is the object referenced by the reference and aimed to be transcluded.

- It can be any type of data (images, text, numbers, audio?...)

## [[transform-1613076164]]

# Mutability vs inmutability

## Strictly inmutable

The [[abstraction-reference-1612699252]] is exclusively [[content-addressed-1625478907]]. This translates to the [[abstraction-reference-1612699252]] being a [[cid-1612383388]] representation

## Mutable

The [[abstraction-reference-1612699252]] can be [[content-addressed-1625478907]] but is not required.
This is very relevant when we want to reference the [[abstraction-intent-1625480615]] instead of its [[content-1625149127]].
In this case we should use [[ipfoam-1612121966]] specfic protocol :
https://docs.libp2p.io/concepts/protocols/

`ipmm/mindId/noteId/propertyId/fragment`
E: I want to reference someone's current [[view-1612896731]] of a subject

Q: What [[ipfoam-property-1613029553]], should be used for the [[transclusion-expression-1613026811]]?
A: It needs to be explicitely defined, the editor can facilitate the task and use a default such as [[prop-title-1612697362]]
